
----------------
Inheritance
-----------
- The process of creating new classes from an existing classes is called as inheritance
- In Java, extends keyword is used to create a new class from an existing class

	Ex:
		class Vehicle //Base or Super or Parent class
		{
		   ...
		}
		class Car extends Vehicle //Derived or Sub or Child class
		{
		   ...
		}

- Through inheritance we can achieve reusability of the code

- Java does not support multiple inheritance due to ambiguities means in Java a class can extend
  only one class

	Ex:
		class A
		{
		   ...
		}
		class B
		{
		   ...
		}
		class C extends A, B {...}//error - does not support multiple inheritance

but in c++ multiple inheritance is supported by to the keyword  virtual ... pointer concept



Ex:

- Inheritance is "is-a" relationship

has-a relationship
------------------
Ex:
	class Book
	{
	  ...
	}

	class Library extends Book {...} //not good Library is a book


	class Library //Library has Book
	{
	   Book book;
	}

Code with example 



class Base {
    int i;
    int j;

    void inputij(int i, int j) {
        this.i = i;
        this.j = j;
    }

    void display() {
        System.out.println("i = " + i + " " + "j =" + j);
    }

}

class Derived extends Base {

    int k;

    void inputk(int k) {
        this.k = k;
    }

    void displayk() {
        System.out.println("k = " + k);
    }
}

public class InheritanceDemo1 {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Base b = new Base();
        b.display(); // i = 0; j = 0 {default value}

        b.inputij(10, 20);
        b.display(); // {i = 10 , j =20}

        Derived d = new Derived();
        d.display(); // i = 0; j = 0 {because when i create a new object i and j are created in
                     // different memory with default value}
        d.inputij(40, 30);
        d.display(); // i = 40 j =30

        d.inputk(100);
        d.displayk(); // k =100
    }
}
